---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import Callout from '@/components/Callout.astro';

const sources = [
  {
    code: 'CPSC',
    name: 'Consumer Product Safety Commission',
    covers: 'Consumer products — toys, electronics, household goods',
    classification: '—',
    lifecycle: '—',
  },
  {
    code: 'FDA',
    name: 'Food & Drug Administration',
    covers: 'Food, drugs, medical devices, cosmetics',
    classification: '1 / 2 / 3 / NC',
    lifecycle: 'Ongoing / Completed / Terminated',
  },
  {
    code: 'USDA',
    name: 'USDA Food Safety & Inspection Service',
    covers: 'Meat, poultry, processed egg products',
    classification: 'Class I / II / III, Public Health Alert',
    lifecycle: 'Active / Closed',
  },
  {
    code: 'NHTSA',
    name: 'National Highway Traffic Safety Administration',
    covers: 'Vehicles and motor-vehicle equipment',
    classification: '—',
    lifecycle: '—',
  },
  {
    code: 'USCG',
    name: 'U.S. Coast Guard',
    covers: 'Recreational boats and equipment',
    classification: 'H / M / L / S',
    lifecycle: 'Open / Closed',
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title="Methodology & caveats"
  description="What this recalls data is and isn't: sources, source-native classifications, the two geography lenses, and the honesty caveats."
>
  <div class="max-w-prose">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold sm:text-4xl">Methodology &amp; caveats</h1>
    <p class="mt-3 text-muted">
      This site aggregates five independent U.S. federal recall feeds into one searchable view. They
      use different vocabularies, scopes, and lifecycles — so we keep each source's data
      <strong>source-native</strong> and never force a false common scale. Here's what that means.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-2xl font-bold">The five sources</h2>
    <div class="mt-3 overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full min-w-[40rem] border-collapse text-left text-sm">
        <thead class="border-b border-line text-xs uppercase text-muted">
          <tr>
            <th class="py-2 pr-3 font-medium">Source</th>
            <th class="py-2 pr-3 font-medium">Covers</th>
            <th class="py-2 pr-3 font-medium">Classification</th>
            <th class="py-2 font-medium">Lifecycle</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {
            sources.map((s) => (
              <tr class="border-b border-line align-top">
                <td class="py-2 pr-3 font-medium">
                  {s.code}
                  <span class="block text-xs font-normal text-muted">{s.name}</span>
                </td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-3">{s.covers}</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-3 font-mono text-xs">{s.classification}</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-xs">{s.lifecycle}</td>
              </tr>
            ))
          }
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-bold">Honesty caveats</h2>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-semibold">Classifications are source-native</h3>
    <p class="mt-1 text-muted">
      FDA uses <code>1/2/3/NC</code>, USDA uses <code>Class I/II/III</code> plus
      <code>Public Health Alert</code>, USCG uses <code>H/M/L/S</code>, and CPSC and NHTSA have
      none. These are <strong>not comparable across agencies</strong> — an FDA "Class 2" is not a USDA
      "Class II". We never show a single global classification legend.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2 text-muted">
      USCG's <code>H/M/L/S</code> codes are a special case: their official meaning is
      <strong>not publicly documented</strong> (the public USCG recall index shows no severity column,
      and 33 CFR 179 defines no such scale). We pass them through verbatim and order them
      <em>provisionally</em> — <code>H/M/L</code> as High/Medium/Low, with <code>S</code> shown last and
      left uncolored — pending confirmation from the Coast Guard. Don't read them as a settled scale.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-semibold">Status is tri-state</h3>
    <p class="mt-1 text-muted">
      Only FDA, USDA, and USCG track an active/inactive lifecycle. CPSC and NHTSA carry none, so
      their recalls show <strong>"No lifecycle"</strong> — not a false "Inactive".
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-semibold">Geography has two distinct lenses</h3>
    <p class="mt-1 text-muted">
      <strong>Distribution</strong> (where a product was sent; FDA/USDA only) and
      <strong>firm registration</strong> (where the responsible firm is registered) answer different questions.
      Registration is <em>not</em> where the product went or where harm occurred. On the
      <a href="/dashboards">dashboards</a> these are two separate maps, never one toggle. Also, a recall
      counts in every state it touches, so per-state counts sum to more than the total.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-semibold">Units recalled aren't comparable</h3>
    <p class="mt-1 text-muted">
      Reported units (NHTSA/USCG) and quantities (FDA/USDA) are a recall-magnitude measure, not
      unique items, and use incommensurable categories (count / weight / volume). Never sum them
      across sources or categories.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-semibold">UPC matching is recall-level and sparse</h3>
    <p class="mt-1 text-muted">
      There is no per-product UPC. UPC search matches a recall-level list that is CPSC-sourced and
      covers only ~5% of CPSC recalls. For vehicles and boats, use the model and HIN fields.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-semibold">"Revised" has no date</h3>
    <p class="mt-1 text-muted">
      A recall marked <strong>revised</strong> means the pipeline detected an editorially-meaningful change
      since first ingest — it is observed-edit evidence, not an official agency amendment, and carries
      no date.
    </p>

    <Callout title="Counts reflect reporting, not risk" class="mt-8">
      <p>
        A source with more recalls isn't "less safe" — counts reflect each agency's reporting scope,
        history, and granularity. Treat cross-source comparisons with care, and read the
        <a href="/api">API reference</a> for field-level provenance. A "no match" in
        <a href="/search">search</a> only covers these five sources.
      </p>
    </Callout>

    <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-bold">How it's built</h2>
    <p class="mt-1 text-muted">
      A Python data pipeline ingests the five feeds nightly into Postgres gold tables; a FastAPI
      service serves them read-only; and this site pulls the slow-moving aggregates at build time
      and fetches per-recall data live. See <a href="/about">about</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</Layout>
